Philemon: Th e apostle in this epistle indulges in some fine
paronomasais on the proper names. Thus Philemon, Φιλημον \[Strong's
G5371\], affectionate, or beloved, is "our dearly beloved;" Apphia
(Απφια \[Strong's G682\], from απφα), the affectionate address of a
brother or sister, according to Suidas), is "the beloved sister," as
several manuscripts, Vulgate, and others correctly read; Archippus
(Αρχιππος \[Strong's G751\], the ruler of the horse, for the managing of
which heros were anciently famous), is "our fellow- soldier;" and
Onesimus (Ονησιμος \[Strong's G3682\], useful or profitable), once
unprofitable, is now profitable., and fellow labourer, [Plm
